'''Dumuzid''', called "the Fisherman" (cuneiform:{{Script/Cuneiform|𒌉𒍣𒋗𒄩}}; [[Sumerian language|Sumerian]]: ''Dumuzid šukud)'',<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://etcsl.orinst.ox.ac.uk/cgi-bin/etcsl.cgi?text=c.2.1.1&display=Crit&charenc=gcirc&lineid=c211.109#c211.109|title=The Electronic Text Corpus of Sumerian Literature|website=etcsl.orinst.ox.ac.uk|access-date=2017-08-29}}</ref> originally from [[Kuara (Sumer)|Kuara]] in [[Sumer]], was the 4th king in the 1st Dynasty of [[Uruk]], and [[Gilgamesh]]'s predecessor, according to the [[Sumerian King List]]. The king list also states that he single handedly captured [[Enmebaragesi]], ruler of [[Kish (Sumer)|Kish]], and claims he ruled in Uruk for 100 years &mdash; far fewer than the 1200 years it ascribes his predecessor, [[Lugalbanda]] "the Shepherd". His given name means "faithful child" in Sumerian. 

There may have been some confusion in the early Sumerian compositions between this figure and that of "[[Dumuzid the Shepherd]]", whom they call the king of Uruk, and who appears as a deity ([[Tammuz (deity)|Tammuz]]) in later works. However, the Sumerian King List says that Dumuzid the ''Shepherd'' had ruled before the flood, and locates him in [[Bad-tibira]].

